 <div v:shape="_x0000_s37890" class=T style='position:absolute;top:9.0%;
 left:13.85%;width:83.14%;height:9.25%'>1.8.4 Types of CSMA/CD</div>
 <div v:shape="_x0000_s37891" class=B>
 <div style='mso-line-spacing:"90 20 -176"'><span style='position:absolute;
 top:25.0%;left:17.6%;width:92.69%'><span style='font-size:75%'><span
 style='mso-special-format:bullet;color:#0099CC;mso-color-index:4;position:
 absolute;left:-4.04%;top:.39em;font-family:"Monotype Sorts";font-size:70%'>n</span></span><span
 style='font-size:75%;color:black'><b>When channel is sensed busy, stations
 wait till it </b></span></span><span style='position:absolute;top:29.75%;
 left:17.6%;width:79.02%'><span style='font-size:75%;color:black'><b>becomes
 idle and then schedule their </b></span></span><span style='position:absolute;
 top:34.5%;left:17.6%;width:86.51%'><span style='font-size:75%;color:black'><b>transmission.
 If length of busy period is long, </b></span></span><span style='position:
 absolute;top:39.25%;left:17.6%;width:92.88%'><span style='font-size:75%;
 color:black'><b>several stations could become active during that </b></span></span><span
 style='position:absolute;top:44.0%;left:17.6%;width:90.63%'><span
 style='font-size:75%;color:black'><b>period and a collision becomes inevitable
 when </b></span></span><span style='position:absolute;top:49.0%;left:17.6%;
 width:87.64%'><span style='font-size:75%;color:black'><b>the channel becomes
 idle again. This is called </b></span></span><span style='position:absolute;
 top:53.75%;left:17.6%;width:90.82%'><span style='font-size:75%;color:#0099CC;
 mso-color-index:4'><b><u>persistent</u></b></span><span style='font-size:75%;
 color:#0099CC;mso-color-index:4'><b> </b></span><span style='font-size:75%;
 color:black'><b>CSMA/CD.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">ï¿½ </span>(IEEE 802.3
 and Ethernet)&#13;</b></span></span></div>
 <div style='mso-line-spacing:"90 20 -176"'><span style='position:absolute;
 top:63.75%;left:17.6%;width:84.64%'><span style='font-size:75%;color:#0099CC;
 mso-color-index:4'><span style='mso-special-format:bullet;position:absolute;
 left:-4.42%;top:.39em;font-family:"Monotype Sorts";font-size:70%'>n</span></span><span
 style='font-size:75%;color:#0099CC;mso-color-index:4'><b><u>Non persistent</u></b></span><span
 style='font-size:75%;color:black'><b> CSMA/CD has stations wait a </b></span></span><span
 style='position:absolute;top:68.5%;left:17.6%;width:90.44%'><span
 style='font-size:75%;color:black'><b>random period whenever the channel is
 sensed </b></span></span><span style='position:absolute;top:73.25%;left:17.6%;
 width:84.08%'><span style='font-size:75%;color:black'><b>busy, i.e, not grab
 it immediately it becomes </b></span></span><span style='position:absolute;
 top:78.0%;left:17.6%;width:93.25%'><span style='font-size:75%;color:black'><b>available.
 Non persistent gives better throughput </b></span></span><span
 style='position:absolute;top:82.75%;left:17.6%;width:83.89%'><span
 style='font-size:75%;color:black'><b>under heavy loading, persistent gives
 better </b></span></span><span style='position:absolute;top:87.5%;left:17.6%;
 width:79.02%'><span style='font-size:75%;color:black'><b>throughput under
 light loads.</b></span></span></div>
 </div>
